[1] Case update
- Mon 6 Aug 2018. Epidemiological situation. Democratic Republic of Congo (North Kivu), Ministry of Health [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=2caaec594a

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease dated 6 Aug 2018:
- a total of 43 cases of haemorrhagic fever were reported in the region, of which 16 confirmed and 27 probable;
- 46 suspected cases are under investigation;
- 2 deaths of confirmed cases, 1 in Beni, and 1 in Mabalako.

News from the Ebola response
- Since the declaration of the new Ebola virus epidemic in North Kivu province on Wed 1 Aug 2018, the National Institute of Biomedical Research (INRB) has carried out a complete sequencing of the genome of the virus to determine whether it is related to the virus that caused the previous epidemic, which occurred a few months earlier in Équateur province. Although the 2 viruses that caused this year's [2018] outbreaks belong to the Ebola Zaire species, the sequencing results confirmed that the virus strains are completely different. This information is important because, on the one hand, it means that the current epidemic in the territory of Beni is a distinct epidemic, unrelated to the previous one in Équateur, and on the other hand, that the vaccine rVSV-ZEBOV can be used as a response strategy.
- The 1st teams of vaccinators will arrive in Beni this Wed 8 Aug 2018. They will begin by vaccinating primary care providers before vaccinating contacts and contacts' contacts.

--
communicated by:
Greg Folkers
NIAID, NIH
