[See URL above for table of cases. Remarks:
- To avoid the total number of cases varying (up or down) daily, the suspect cases have been placed in a separate category. Thus, suspect cases with positive laboratory tests will be added to the confirmed category, while negative ones (non-cases) will be removed from the table.
- The category of probable cases includes all reported deaths for which it was not possible to obtain biological samples for laboratory confirmation. The investigations will determine whether these deaths are related to the epidemic or not.

Note that the number of cases (deaths) reported from Ituri are now listed as 2 (including 2 deaths) rather the 5 reported earlier. See ProMED-mail Ebola update (61): Congo DR (NK) WHO, cases, response 20180806.5950109 for report on Ituri not having cases.

Also see the URL above for maps showing the location of outbreaks.]

- Tue 7 Aug 2018. Ebola virus disease - Democratic Republic of Congo, WHO/AFRO external situation report 01
[WHO AFRO Outbreaks <afrooutbreak@who.int> edited]
http://newsletters.afro.who.int/outbreak-dashboards/1hdr3zya55u1it646w1k05?email=true&a=11&p=53722888

On 1 Aug 2018, the Ministry of Health of the Democratic Republic of the Congo notified WHO of a new outbreak of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in North Kivu province, in the eastern part of the country. The event was initially reported by the North Kivu Provincial Health Authority on 28 Jul 2018 when a cluster of 26 cases of acute haemorrhagic fever, including 20 deaths (mostly in the community), occurred in Mabalako Health Zone during mid-late July 2018. Local health officials additionally identified sporadic, antecedent deaths in the community since May 2018 (tentatively classified as probable cases), which are subject to ongoing investigations to determine if they are related to the current outbreak.

Blood specimens collected from 6 hospitalized case-patients on 31 Aug 2018 were shipped to the Institut National de Recherche Biomédicale (INRB) in Kinshasa. On 1 Aug 2018, 4 of the 6 blood specimens tested positive for Ebolavirus by GeneXpert automated-polymerase chain reaction (PCR). The Ministry of Health Officially declared the outbreak on 1 Aug 2018. Further laboratory testing by INRB confirmed Ebolavirus in 3 of the initial 6 specimens using conventional PCR. The result of the genetic analysis by INRB confirmed Ebola Zaire strain, but not linked to the Équateur outbreak strain, meaning that we are dealing with a new outbreak.

As of 5 Aug 2018, a total of 43 EVD cases, including 34 deaths, have been reported. Between 3 and 4 Aug 2018, 12 specimens tested positive at the field-based laboratory in Beni City, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 16. A total of 27 cases are classified as probable. Of the 34 deaths, 7 occurred in confirmed cases. 2 healthcare workers have been affected, of which 1 died. An additional 31 suspected cases are currently being investigated and awaiting laboratory results to confirm or exclude EVD.

To date, 6 health zones in 2 provinces have reported confirmed and probable EVD cases, including Mabalako, Beni, Butembo, Oicha, and Musienene health zones in North Kivu province and Mandina Health Zone in Ituri province.

Context
-------
The province of North Kivu is among the most populated provinces, with 8 million inhabitants. It shares borders with 4 other provinces (Ituri, South Kivu, Maniema, and Tshopo) as well as with Uganda and Rwanda. The subregion has been experiencing intense insecurity and worsening humanitarian crisis, with over 1 million internally displaced people and a continuous efflux of refugees to the neighbouring countries, including Uganda, Burundi, and Tanzania.

--
